\n**WHAT'S GOING ON**\nRJ Scaringe, the founder of the electric truck company Rivian, realized that standard factory robots are completely stumped by the unexpected [3, 4]. So, he started a new company called Mind Robotics [4]. Instead of just writing code in a clean lab, they are dropping a vertically integrated system of physical machines and AI brains right onto the active Rivian factory floors [2, 5]. They are forcing artificial intelligence to deal with the messy reality of building cars.\n\n**WHY THIS IS A BIG DEAL**\nLook, standard industrial robots are fantastic at doing the exact same motion a million times\u2014like welding a joint at a precise coordinate [3]. But if a wire wiggles or a piece of material flexes a fraction of a millimeter, the traditional robot just fails [3]. The real world is full of wiggles! Mind Robotics is trying to fix this by giving robots the \"brain\" to actually observe a floppy wiring harness, understand what is happening, and use physical dexterity to install it anyway [3]. By hooking these robots directly into a live, high-speed manufacturing line, they get a massive, continuous feedback loop of real data [5]. If they crack this, we finally transition from computers that just *think* to machines that can actually *act* in chaotic, dynamic physical environments [1].\n\n**UNCOMFORTABLE TRUTH**\nIn software, if your AI makes a mistake\u2014what we call a hallucination\u2014you just get a weird sentence or a bad image. You hit refresh [3]. In a factory, if an AI-driven robot hallucinates, it smashes a multi-million dollar machine, ruins the product, or hurts someone. The physical world simply does not forgive bad math [3]. We do not actually know for certain yet if learning models can consistently hit the extreme, micron-level tolerances required for heavy industry without catastrophic failures [3]. \n\n**SO WHAT**\nWe are finally pushing artificial intelligence out of the safety of the web browser and into the heavy, unforgiving machinery of the physical economy [1, 6].",
